For whoever cares to hear about it, there is massive defrauding of the taxpayers occurring at FCI Thomson in Illinois. It is a federal prison that used to be a state super max, but it got shut down after being deemed inhumane. The feds bought the vacant building and turned it into a low-security prison, and now have about 2000 inmates there. Approximately half the staff at FCI Thomson used to work at the super-max, and during that time their pay was substantially higher. Why? Because at a super-max, staff members automatically get hazard pay.So, how is the administration trying to make up for the pay reduction? Why, by putting the entire prison on lockdown continuously of course.In the feds, going on lockdown means keeping all the inmates in the 2 man cells continuously, which effectively turns the whole prison into the SHU. It has the side-effect of cutting the inmates off from any physical means of communication to the outside. And it also has the side-effect of ensuring that all the guards and staff make huge amounts of overtime whilst actually performing less work. Although their shifts become longer, all the programming and most administrative request processes become disabled. The guards at Thomson go a little bit further by only letting the kitchen staff out for a few hours during lockdowns, so the guards do not even have to take over cooking / passing out the food either (except for unlocking the small slot on the door).The general idea behind lockdowns in the feds is that they are supposed to be an extraordinary measure in response to some extreme danger. Basically, if there's a race riot or a gang war, a prison will go on lockdown. Its not supposed to be the normal status of a prison, because it will eventually make people go violent and crazy. At FCI Thomson, they spent ~3 months out of the last year on lockdown, and so far in 2025 they have spent 40 days on lockdown. We are only 3 months into the year, and this is for low-security inmates!

For whoever cares to hear about it, there is massive defrauding of the taxpayers occurring at FCI Thomson in Illinois. It is a federal prison that used to be a state super max, but it got shut down after being deemed inhumane. The feds bought the vacant building and turned it into a low-security prison, and now have about 2000 inmates there. Approximately half the staff at FCI Thomson used to work at the super-max, and during that time their pay was substantially higher. Why? Because at a super-max, staff members automatically get hazard pay.So, how is the administration trying to make up for the pay reduction? Why, by putting the entire prison on lockdown continuously of course.In the feds, going on lockdown means keeping all the inmates in the 2 man cells continuously, which effectively turns the whole prison into the SHU. It has the side-effect of cutting the inmates off from any physical means of communication to the outside. And it also has the side-effect of ensuring that all the guards and staff make huge amounts of overtime whilst actually performing less work. Although their shifts become longer, all the programming and most administrative request processes become disabled. The guards at Thomson go a little bit further by only letting the kitchen staff out for a few hours during lockdowns, so the guards do not even have to take over cooking / passing out the food either (except for unlocking the small slot on the door).The general idea behind lockdowns in the feds is that they are supposed to be an extraordinary measure in response to some extreme danger. Basically, if there's a race riot or a gang war, a prison will go on lockdown. Its not supposed to be the normal status of a prison, because it will eventually make people go violent and crazy. At FCI Thomson, they spent ~3 months out of the last year on lockdown, and so far in 2025 they have spent 40 days on lockdown. We are only 3 months into the year, and this is for low-security inmates!

>Ending Federal Oversight on Civil Rights - Without the DOE enforcing anti-discrimination laws, schools would no longer be pressured to integrate or adhere to forced diversity measures. Local districts could establish their own policies that better reflect the values and demographics of their communities.>Redirecting Funding to Neighborhood Schools - Federal funding often takes money from wealthier areas and redistributes it to low-income districts. Without the DOE, tax dollars could stay within their own communities, ensuring that schools reflect the economic and cultural priorities of the families they serve.>Allowing Local Control Over Education Policy - Instead of being subject to one-size-fits-all federal mandates, states and districts could create education policies that cater to their own populations. This could lead to more traditional schooling environments where communities can uphold their own standards without outside influence.>Expanding School Choice and Private Education - Removing the DOE would likely lead to more school choice, including private schools, charter schools, and voucher programs. This would allow families to select schools that align with their values and academic expectations rather than being forced into government-mandated integration programs.>Eliminating Forced Integration Programs - Programs designed to mix student populations across racial and economic lines, such as busing or magnet schools, would no longer receive federal support. Schools would naturally reflect the composition of their neighborhoods, allowing for a more homogenous and culturally cohesive learning environment.By dismantling the DOE, education would return to local and parental control, ensuring that schools serve the interests of their own communities rather than being shaped by federal policies aimed at forced integration.

For whoever cares to hear about it, there is massive defrauding of the taxpayers occurring at FCI Thomson in Illinois. It is a federal prison that used to be a state super max, but it got shut down after being deemed inhumane. The feds bought the vacant building and turned it into a low-security prison, and now have about 2000 inmates there. Approximately half the staff at FCI Thomson used to work at the super-max, and during that time their pay was substantially higher. Why? Because at a super-max, staff members automatically get hazard pay.So, how is the administration trying to make up for the pay reduction? Why, by putting the entire prison on lockdown continuously of course.In the feds, going on lockdown means keeping all the inmates in the 2 man cells continuously, which effectively turns the whole prison into the SHU. It has the side-effect of cutting the inmates off from any physical means of communication to the outside. And it also has the side-effect of ensuring that all the guards and staff make huge amounts of overtime whilst actually performing less work. Although their shifts become longer, all the programming and most administrative request processes become disabled. The guards at Thomson go a little bit further by only letting the kitchen staff out for a few hours during lockdowns, so the guards do not even have to take over cooking / passing out the food either (except for unlocking the small slot on the door).The general idea behind lockdowns in the feds is that they are supposed to be an extraordinary measure in response to some extreme danger. Basically, if there's a race riot or a gang war, a prison will go on lockdown. Its not supposed to be the normal status of a prison, because it will eventually make people go violent and crazy. At FCI Thomson, they spent ~3 months out of the last year on lockdown, and so far in 2025 they have spent 40 days on lockdown. We are only 3 months into the year, and this is for low-security inmates!
